            <!-- Drywall Problems -->
            <article class="material-card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                <div class="h-48 overflow-hidden">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1600585154340-043788447eb5?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" 
                         alt="Drywall Problems" 
                         class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-110">
                </div>
                <div class="p-6">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900 text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300 text-xs font-semibold rounded-full">
                            Drywall
                        </span>
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
                        10 Signs of Drywall Problems And How to Fix Them
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
                        Drywall is one of the most common materials used in modern homes to create smooth interior walls and ceilings. However, it can develop problems over time including cracks, nail pops, water damage, mold, and sagging. Most issues stem from moisture, settling, or improper installation. Early detection and proper repair techniques prevent more extensive damage and maintain your home's appearance.
                    </p>
                    <button onclick="openModal(4)" class="inline-flex items-center text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400 font-medium hover:text-primary-800 dark:hover:text-primary-300 text-sm cursor-pointer">
                        Read Guide <i class="ri-arrow-right-line ml-2"></i>
                    </button>
                </div>
            </article>

            <!-- What is Drywall -->
            <article class="material-card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                <div class="h-48 overflow-hidden">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507136566006-cfc505b114fc?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" 
                         alt="What is Drywall" 
                         class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-110">
                </div>
                <div class="p-6">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900 text-purple-800 dark:text-purple-300 text-xs font-semibold rounded-full">
                            Materials
                        </span>
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
                        What is Drywall? A Guide on Types, Uses & Installation
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
                        Have you ever wondered what's behind the smooth walls in your house? Most likely, it's drywall-a building material that covers the inside of homes and buildings. Drywall consists of gypsum plaster pressed between two layers of paper. It's fire-resistant, relatively inexpensive, and easy to install. Types include standard, moisture-resistant (green board), and fire-rated (Type X) drywall.
                    </p>
                    <button onclick="openModal(5)" class="inline-flex items-center text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400 font-medium hover:text-primary-800 dark:hover:text-primary-300 text-sm cursor-pointer">
                        Read Guide <i class="ri-arrow-right-line ml-2"></i>
                    </button>
                </div>
            </article>

            <!-- Built Up Roof -->
            <article class="material-card bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lg border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                <div class="h-48 overflow-hidden">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558036117-15e82a2c9a9a?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" 
                         alt="Built Up Roof" 
                         class="w-full h-full object-cover transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-110">
                </div>
                <div class="p-6">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-indigo-100 dark:bg-indigo-900 text-indigo-800 dark:text-indigo-300 text-xs font-semibold rounded-full">
                            Roofing
                        </span>
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
                        What is a Built Up Roof? Why It Still Works Best
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
                        When it comes to protecting large commercial buildings from the elements, few systems have stood the test of time like the built-up roof, or BUR. This roofing system consists of multiple layers of bitumen and reinforcing fabrics creating a durable, waterproof membrane. BUR systems offer excellent durability, fire resistance, and are relatively easy to repair compared to single-ply membranes.
                    </p>
                    <button onclick="openModal(6)" class="inline-flex items-center text-primary-600 dark:text-primary-400 font-medium hover:text-primary-800 dark:hover:text-primary-300 text-sm cursor-pointer">
                        Read Guide <i class="ri-arrow-right-line ml-2"></i>
                    </button>
